  "physics_explanation": "Two independent Type-II SPDC sources each produce entangled pairs in state (|HV\u27e9 + |VH\u27e9)/\u221a2. The H-polarized photons from both sources are directed to a polarizing beam splitter (fusion PBS) where they undergo Hong-Ou-Mandel interference. When both H photons exit together to detector C (post-selected event), the V-polarized photons at detectors A and B become entangled with the fused photon, creating the three-photon GHZ state |GHZ\u27e9 = (|VVH\u27e9 + |HHV\u27e9)/\u221a2 through entanglement swapping and quantum interference.",
  "expected_outcome": "Triple coincidence measurements between detectors A, B, and C reveal GHZ state correlations. In the HV basis, measurements show correlated outcomes with two V-polarized and one H-polarized photon. Measurements in rotated bases (diagonal/anti-diagonal or circular) will violate the Mermin inequality, demonstrating genuine three-photon entanglement that exceeds classical bounds. The post-selected coincidence rate is reduced due to fusion gate success probability, but detected triple events exhibit maximal three-party entanglement characteristic of the GHZ state with fidelity limited by spectral distinguishability and detector efficiency.",
